The election outcome was, to all intents and purposes, a carbon copy of 1997. The Labour Party maintained its substantial majority, with the BBC declaring victory in the early hours of 8 June. Having presided over a period of relative political, economic, and social calm, the prevailing sense of prosperity in the United Kingdom had carried into the new millennium, granting Labour a clear mandate to pursue its agenda in the subsequent parliamentary term. Despite this electoral success, voter apathy remained a significant concern, as turnout fell below 60%, a decline of 12 percentage points from 1997. All three major parties experienced a reduction in their overall vote counts: Labour's vote dropped by 2.8 million, the Conservatives' by 1.3 million, and the Liberal Democrats' by 428,000. Some interpreted this dramatic decrease as a sign of widespread acceptance of the status quo and a confirmation that Labour's majority was likely to remain unassailable.

For the Conservatives, the profound losses of 1997 were largely replicated. Despite securing nine gains, they simultaneously lost seven seats to the Liberal Democrats and one to Labour ([South Dorset](/South_Dorset_(UK_Parliament_constituency))). [William Hague](/William_Hague) promptly announced his resignation at 07:44 outside Conservative Party headquarters. While some observers considered Hague to have been unfortunate, and indeed acknowledged his talents as an orator and statesman, he ultimately faced the charismatic [Tony Blair](/Tony_Blair) at the zenith of his political influence. It was therefore unsurprising that little headway was made in reducing Labour's majority, particularly after a relatively uneventful parliamentary term.

Remaining at what they likely perceived as rock bottom, the Conservatives demonstrated a failure to improve their negative public image, continued to be fractured by internal divisions over Europe, and had not regained the trust lost in the preceding decade. Hague's focus on the "Save The Pound" campaign narrative proved ineffective. Labour's counter-strategy was to maintain a deliberate vagueness on the issue of future monetary union, stating only that the UK would consider joining the Eurozone "when conditions were right." In [Scotland](/2001_United_Kingdom_general_election_in_Scotland), despite gaining one seat from the [Scottish National Party](/Scottish_National_Party), the Conservatives' vote collapse persisted. They failed to recapture former strongholds, with the Nationalists consolidating their influence in the northeastern part of the country.

The Liberal Democrats could, at least, point to steady progress under their new leader, [Charles Kennedy](/Charles_Kennedy). They achieved more seat gains than either of the two larger parties, albeit a modest six in total. This performance echoed the positive results of the 1997 election, where the party had doubled its seat count to 46. While they had not yet established themselves as a credible alternative government, they solidified their growing reputation as a viable option to Labour and Conservative, contributing significantly to parliamentary debate and representing more than just a protest vote.

The SNP failed to secure any new seats and lost one to the Conservatives by a mere 79 votes. In [Wales](/2001_United_Kingdom_general_election_in_Wales), [Plaid Cymru](/Plaid_Cymru) managed to gain one seat from Labour ([Carmarthen East and Dinefwr](/Carmarthen_East_and_Dinefwr_(UK_Parliament_constituency))) but lost another ([Ynys Môn](/Ynys_M%C3%B4n_(UK_Parliament_constituency))) to them.

In [Northern Ireland](/2001_United_Kingdom_general_election_results_in_Northern_Ireland), the Ulster Unionists, despite gaining [North Down](/North_Down_(UK_Parliament_constituency)), lost five other seats.

